    "summary": "Ptolemaic Alexandria (305–30 BC) was the most cosmopolitan city of the ancient world — a planned Hellenistic metropolis on the Egyptian coast that became the largest city in the Mediterranean and a global center of scholarship, commerce, and cultural synthesis. Founded by Alexander the Great on a narrow strip between the sea and Lake Mareotis, it was designed with wide boulevards, a royal quarter (Brucheion), a Jewish quarter (one of the world's largest Jewish diaspora communities), a commercial harbor, and the royal palace complex housing the Mouseion and Great Library.\n\nAlexandria's cultural achievement during the Ptolemaic period was extraordinary: the Library aimed to collect all human knowledge and employed the greatest scholars of the Hellenistic world; the Lighthouse of Alexandria (Pharos) was one of the Seven Wonders of the ancient world; and the city's population — Macedonian Greeks, native Egyptians, Jews, Syrians, and others — produced hybrid cultural forms including the [[event:1151|Septuagint Translation]] of the Hebrew Bible into Greek. The city's intellectual tradition was both preserved and developed Roman-era Neoplatonism and early Christianity. Alexandria was the largest producer of papyrus manuscripts in the ancient world and the model for the idea of a universal library that has inspired institutions to the present day.",
